- We could consider each minute of Bruno's journey as a term of a geometric sequence, and we need the sum of the first 10 terms to determine how far Bruno travels between $8$:$30$ and $8$:$40$ am.
  We have a geometric sequence with the first term $u_1 = 160$ and common ratio $r = 0.8$.
  If we use the sum of $n$ terms formula $S_n = \dfrac{u_1(1-r^n)}{1-r}$ with $n=10$, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  S_{10} &= \dfrac{u_1(1-r^{10})}{1-r} \\[6pt]
  &= \dfrac{160(1-0.8^{10})}{1-0.8} \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[12pt]
  &= 714.10... \tag*{\textbf{A1}} \\[6pt]
  714.10... &< 750 \tag*{\textbf{R1}}
  \end{align*}    
  $$

  Bruno will only travel $714$ metres by $8$:$40$ am, which is less than the $750$ metres required.
  Therefore, Bruno $\textbf{will not}$ arrive at school on time.
