- The height of the ball after each bounce follows a geometric sequence, with first term $u_1 = 5(0.89)$ and common ratio $r = 0.89$.
  Using the formula for the $n$th term of a geometric sequence, we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  u_{2} &= u_1r^{2-1} \\[6pt]
  &= [5(0.89)](0.89)^1 \\[7pt]
  &\hspace{0.275em}\tcbhighmath{\approx 3.96\text{ m}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- The total distance travelled by the ball is the sum of two separate geometric sequences.
  The first, when the ball is travelling downwards, has first term $u_1=5$ and common ratio $r=0.89$. When the ball hits the ground for the $5$th time, it has travelled downwards a distance that is equivalent to the sum of the first five terms of this sequence. We have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  S_n &= \dfrac{u_1(1-r^n)}{1-r} \\[6pt]
  S_5 &= \dfrac{5(1-0.89^5)}{1-0.89} \\[7pt]
  &\approx 20.07 \,\text{m}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  The second, when the ball is travelling upwards, has first term $u_1=5(0.89)$ and common ratio $r=0.89$. When the ball hits the ground for the $5$th time, it has travelled upwards a distance that is equivalent to the sum of the first four terms of this sequence. We have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  S_n &= \dfrac{u_1(1-r^n)}{1-r} \\[6pt]
  S_4 &= \dfrac{5(0.89)(1-0.89^4)}{1-0.89} \\[7pt]
  &\approx 15.07 \,\text{m}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  The total distance travelled is given by $20.07 + 15.07$.
  The total distance travelled by the ball is approximately $\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{35.1\,\text{metres}}$.

The time Aoife takes daily to complete her deliveries follows an $\textbf{arithmetic sequence}$, with first term $u_1=240$ and common difference $d=-2$.
The time Barack takes daily to complete his deliveries follows a $\textbf{geometric sequence}$ with first term $v_1=240$ and common ratio $r$.
Given that Barack is $\textit{reducing}$ his time by $1\%$ per day, this means that each day his deliveries take $99\%$ of the time of the day before. Therefore $r=0.99$.
We are looking for the first day that Aoife will complete her deliveries faster than Barack. Let's call this day $n$.
We are therfore looking for the smallest value of $n$ such that $u_n < v_n$.
Using the formula for the $n$th term of an arithmetic sequence, we have

$$
\begin{align*}
    u_n &= u_1 + (n-1)d \\[6pt]
    &= 240 + (n-1)(-2) \\[6pt]
    &= 240 -2n + 2 \\[6pt]
    u_n &= 242 - 2n \tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
\end{align*}
$$

Using the formula for the $n$th term of a geometric sequence, we have

$$
\begin{align*}
    v_n &= v_1\,r^{n-1} \\[6pt]
    &= 240(0.99)^{n-1} \tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
\end{align*}
$$

Hence we are trying determine the smallest value of $n$ so that

$$
\begin{align*}
    242 - 2n < 240(0.99)^{n-1} \tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
\end{align*}
$$

To do this, we will sketch and interpret the graphs of $y=242-2x$ and $y=240(0.99)^{x-1}$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
\end{aligned}
$$

